    {
      "content": "What is a Network Security Group (NSG)",
      "pos": [
        27,
        65
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Learn about Network Security Groups (NSG)",
      "pos": [
        83,
        124
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What is a Network Security Group (NSG)?",
      "pos": [
        447,
        486
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use an NSG to control traffic to one or more virtual machine (VM) instances in your virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        488,
        596
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A network security group is a top level object that is associated to your subscription An NSG contains access control rules that allow or deny traffic to VM instances.",
      "pos": [
        597,
        764
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The rules of an NSG can be changed at any time, and changes are applied to all associated instances.",
      "pos": [
        765,
        865
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To use an NSG, you must have a VNet that is associated with a region (location).",
      "pos": [
        866,
        946
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.WARNING]</ph> NSGs are not compatible with VNets that are associated with an affinity group.",
      "pos": [
        950,
        1044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you don’t have a regional VNet and you want to control traffic to your endpoints, please see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>What is a Network Access Control List (ACL)?<ept id=\"p1\">](./virtual-networks-acl.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1045,
        1215
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>migrate your VNet to a regional VNet<ept id=\"p1\">](./virtual-networks-migrate-to-regional-vnet.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1216,
        1316
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can associate an NSG to a VM, or to a subnet within a VNet.",
      "pos": [
        1318,
        1381
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When associated with a VM, the NSG applies to all the traffic that is sent and received by the VM instance.",
      "pos": [
        1382,
        1489
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When applied to a subnet within your VNet, it applies to all the traffic that is sent and received by ALL the VM instances in the subnet.",
      "pos": [
        1490,
        1627
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A VM or subnet can be associated with only 1 NSG, and each NSG can contain up to 200 rules.",
      "pos": [
        1628,
        1719
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can have 100 NSGs per subscription.",
      "pos": [
        1720,
        1759
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Endpoint-based ACLs and network security groups are not supported on the same VM instance.",
      "pos": [
        1762,
        1865
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you want to use an NSG and have an endpoint ACL already in place, first remove the endpoint ACL.",
      "pos": [
        1866,
        1965
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For information about how to do this, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Managing Access Control Lists (ACLs) for Endpoints by using PowerShell<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-networks-acl-powershell.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1966,
        2117
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How does a network security group work?",
      "pos": [
        2122,
        2161
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Network security groups are different than endpoint-based ACLs.",
      "pos": [
        2163,
        2226
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Endpoint ACLs work only on the public port that is exposed through the input endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        2227,
        2313
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An NSG works on one or more VM instances and controls all the traffic that is inbound and outbound on the VM.",
      "pos": [
        2314,
        2423
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A network security group has a <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Name<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, is associated to a <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Region<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>, and has a descriptive label.",
      "pos": [
        2425,
        2521
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It contains two types of rules, <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Inbound<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Outbound<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2522,
        2583
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Inbound rules are applied on the incoming packets to a VM and the Outbound rules are applied to the outgoing packets from the VM.",
      "pos": [
        2584,
        2717
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The rules are applied at the host where the VM is located.",
      "pos": [
        2718,
        2776
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An incoming or outgoing packet has to match an <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Allow<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> rule for it be permitted, if not it will be dropped.",
      "pos": [
        2777,
        2886
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Rules are processed in the order of priority.",
      "pos": [
        2888,
        2933
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, a rule with a lower priority number (e.g. 100) is processed before rules with a higher priority numbers (e.g. 200).",
      "pos": [
        2934,
        3062
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once a match is found, no more rules are processed.",
      "pos": [
        3063,
        3114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A rule specifies the following:",
      "pos": [
        3116,
        3147
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3151,
        3193
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Name:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> A unique identifier for the rule"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3197,
        3223
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Type:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Inbound/Outbound"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3227,
        3290
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Priority:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> &lt;You can specify an integer between 100 and 4096&gt;"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3294,
        3340
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Source IP Address:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> CIDR of source IP range"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3344,
        3405
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Source Port Range:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> &lt;integer or range between 0 and 65536&gt;"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3409,
        3467
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Destination IP Range:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> CIDR of the destination IP Range"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3471,
        3537
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Destination Port Range:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> &lt;integer or range between 0 and 65536&gt;"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3541,
        3583
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Protocol:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> &lt;TCP, UDP or ‘*’ is allowed&gt;"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3587,
        3609
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Access:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Allow/Deny"
    },
    {
      "content": "Default Rules",
      "pos": [
        3615,
        3628
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An NSG contains default rules.",
      "pos": [
        3630,
        3660
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default rules cannot be deleted, but because they are assigned the lowest priority, they can be overridden by the rules that you create.",
      "pos": [
        3661,
        3801
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default rules describe the default settings recommended by the platform.",
      "pos": [
        3802,
        3878
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As illustrated by the default rules below, traffic originating and ending in a VNet is allowed both in Inbound and Outbound directions.",
      "pos": [
        3879,
        4014
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While connectivity to the Internet is allowed for Outbound direction, it is by default blocked for Inbound direction.",
      "pos": [
        4016,
        4133
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is a default rule to allow Azure’s load balancer (LB) to probe the health of the VM.",
      "pos": [
        4134,
        4224
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can override this rule if the VM or set of VMs under the NSG does not participate in the load balanced set.",
