    {
      "content": "Special Infrastructure Rules",
      "pos": [
        5740,
        5768
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "NSG rules are explicit.",
      "pos": [
        5770,
        5793
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "No traffic is allowed or denied beyond what is specified in the NSG rules.",
      "pos": [
        5794,
        5868
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, there are two types of traffic that are always allowed regardless of the Network Security group specification.",
      "pos": [
        5869,
        5988
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These provisions are made to support the infrastructure.",
      "pos": [
        5989,
        6045
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Virtual IP of the Host Node:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Basic infrastructure services such as DHCP, DNS, and Health monitoring are provided through the virtualized host IP address 168.63.129.16.",
      "pos": [
        6049,
        6220
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This public IP address belongs to Microsoft and will be the only virtualized IP address used in all regions for this purpose.",
      "pos": [
        6221,
        6346
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This IP address maps to the physical IP address of the server machine (host node) hosting the virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        6347,
        6457
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The host node acts as the DHCP relay, the DNS recursive resolver, and the probe source for the load balancer health probe and the machine health probe.",
      "pos": [
        6458,
        6609
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Communication to this IP address should not be considered as an attack.",
      "pos": [
        6610,
        6681
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Licensing (Key Management Service):<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Windows images running in the virtual machines should be licensed.",
      "pos": [
        6685,
        6791
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To do this, a licensing request is sent to the Key Management Service host servers that handle such queries.",
      "pos": [
        6792,
        6900
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This will always be on outbound port 1688.",
      "pos": [
        6901,
        6943
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Default Tags",
      "pos": [
        6949,
        6961
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Default tags are system-provided identifiers to address a category of IP addresses.",
      "pos": [
        6963,
        7046
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Default tags can be specified in customer defined rules.",
      "pos": [
        7047,
        7103
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default tags are as follows:",
      "pos": [
        7104,
        7136
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>VIRTUAL_NETWORK -<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> This default tag denotes all of your network address space.",
      "pos": [
        7140,
        7221
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It includes the virtual network address space (IP CIDR in Azure) as well as all connected on-premises address space (Local Networks).",
      "pos": [
        7222,
        7355
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This also includes VNet to VNet address spaces.",
      "pos": [
        7356,
        7403
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>AZURE_LOADBALANCER -<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> This default tag denotes Azure’s Infrastructure load balancer.",
      "pos": [
        7407,
        7494
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This will translate to an Azure datacenter IP where Azure’s health probes will originate.",
      "pos": [
        7495,
        7584
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is needed only if the VM or set of VMs associated with the NSG is participating in a load balanced set.",
      "pos": [
        7585,
        7693
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>INTERNET -<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> This default tag denotes the IP Address space that is outside the virtual network and reachable by public Internet.",
      "pos": [
        7697,
        7827
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This range includes Azure owned public IP space as well.",
      "pos": [
        7828,
        7884
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Ports and Port Ranges",
      "pos": [
        7890,
        7911
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Network security group rules can be specified on a single source/destination port, or on a port range.",
      "pos": [
        7913,
        8015
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is particularly useful in cases where you want to open a wide range of ports for an application, such as FTP.",
      "pos": [
        8016,
        8130
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The range can only be sequential and cannot be mixed with individual port specification.",
      "pos": [
        8131,
        8219
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8221,
        8323
      ],
      "content": "To specify a range of ports, use the ‘-’ sign, as shown below in the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>DestinationPortRange<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> parameter:"
    },
    {
      "content": "ICMP Traffic",
      "pos": [
        8608,
        8620
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The current NSG rules only allow for protocols ‘TCP’ or ‘UDP’.",
      "pos": [
        8622,
        8684
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is not a specific tag for ‘ICMP’.",
      "pos": [
        8685,
        8724
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, ICMP traffic is allowed within a Virtual Network by default through the Inbound VNet rules that allow traffic from/to any port and protocol  ‘*’ within the VNet.",
      "pos": [
        8725,
        8895
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Associating NSGs",
      "pos": [
        8900,
        8916
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Associating an NSG to a VM - When an NSG is directly associated to a VM, the Network access rules in the NSG are directly applied to all traffic that is destined to the VM.",
      "pos": [
        8918,
        9090
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Whenever the NSG is updated for rule changes, the changes are reflected in the traffic handling within minutes.",
      "pos": [
        9091,
        9202
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the NSG is dis-associated from the VM, the state goes back to whatever it was before the NSG, i.e. the system defaults before the introduction if NSG will be used.",
      "pos": [
        9203,
        9371
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Associating an NSG to a Subnet - When an NSG is associated to a subnet, the Network access rules in the NSG are applied to all the VMs in the subnet.",
      "pos": [
        9373,
        9522
      ]
    },
    {
